  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1990375463" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1990375463" />
    <a title="Bryan--Pumpkin Connoisseur" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16951301-bryan--pumpkin-connoisseur"><img alt="Bryan--Pumpkin Connoisseur" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1602184090p2/16951301.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1990375463?book_show_action=true">May 03, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bryan--Pumpkin Connoisseur" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bryan--Pumpkin Connoisseur" href="/user/show/16951301-bryan--pumpkin-connoisseur">Bryan--Pumpkin Connoisseur</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16951301-bryan--pumpkin-connoisseur?shelf=books-i-read-in-2018">books-i-read-in-2018</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16951301-bryan--pumpkin-connoisseur?shelf=guardian-read">guardian-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1990375463" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3860628460070963455"><i>The Magnificent Ambersons</i>, to me, belongs in that naturalistic run of American novels that also includes things like <i>Sister Carrie</i> by Dreiser, and probably dozens of others, and which are intent on getting at what it means to be American while at the same time faithfully recording &apos;the way it is&apos; (or was, depending on your relative position in time, I suppose). As such, I appreciate these novels for the picture they portray and the craft of the storyteller and the entertainment value of the plot</span>
  <span id="freeText3860628460070963455" style="display:none"><i>The Magnificent Ambersons</i>, to me, belongs in that naturalistic run of American novels that also includes things like <i>Sister Carrie</i> by Dreiser, and probably dozens of others, and which are intent on getting at what it means to be American while at the same time faithfully recording 'the way it is' (or was, depending on your relative position in time, I suppose). As such, I appreciate these novels for the picture they portray and the craft of the storyteller and the entertainment value of the plot, but these novels do not seem to go any deeper (not that they are required to): thus I see a great gulf between something like <i>The Magnificent Ambersons</i> and, say <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/261441.USA_The_42nd_Parallel___1919___The_Big_Money" title="USA The 42nd Parallel / 1919 / The Big Money by John Dos Passos" rel="nofollow noopener">USA</a> by Dos Passos, even though superficially they can look very similar. It's a distinction that's difficult to put into words, though I know it when I read it. Perhaps I would say that the first uses its characters to illustrate a time and place, the second uses time and place to reveal aspects of the human character.<br /><br />Neither one is inherently better than the other. I enjoyed <i>The Magnificent Ambersons</i>--it isn't completely documentary, and Tarkington's prose is engaging. In fact, I gulped down the last half of the book at one sitting, when I should have been sleeping. I know it sounds as though I've been criticizing it for lacking a kind of 'depth', but that would be like criticizing <i>The Godfather</i> for not being <i>Goodfellas</i>.<br /><br />MA concentrates mostly on George Amberson Minafer, grandson of 'The Major' who initially gathered the Amberson fortune and became the town's most prominent citizen. Initially a prince of the city, it is fated for George to be the captain of the dissolution of the Amberson name, as time and technology wait for no man, and the world simply passes him by. <br /><br />Tarkington won the Pulitzer for <i>MA</i>, and again a few years later for <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/525818.Alice_Adams" title="Alice Adams by Booth Tarkington" rel="nofollow noopener">Alice Adams</a>. As this is part of a challenge to read the Pulitzer winners in order, I'll be trying more Tarkington in the near future if I hold out, and based on <i>The Magnificent Ambersons</i>, it should be an enjoyable experience.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3860628460070963455" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


