    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_64366601" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/64366601" />
    <a title="Dusty" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/655483-dusty"><img alt="Dusty" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1605501426p2/655483.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/64366601?book_show_action=true">Jul 21, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dusty" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dusty" href="/user/show/655483-dusty">Dusty</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/655483-dusty?shelf=carly-dusty-book-club">carly-dusty-book-club</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/655483-dusty?shelf=read-in-2009">read-in-2009</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/655483-dusty?shelf=read-in-2016">read-in-2016</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/655483-dusty?shelf=pulitzer-winners">pulitzer-winners</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer64366601" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8647704863726004547"><b>Update:</b> The first time I read <i>Ambersons</i>, oh so many years ago, I was entranced. I felt I had stumbled upon a lost treasure and was equally repulsed and bewitched by the character at the center, young Georgie Minafer. After reading it a second time, my admiration for the Georgie character is unchanged, even as I find myself questioning other aspects of the book. In particular, I object to the presentation of the book&apos;s few African American characters and think Tarkington ultimately goes too easy </span>
  <span id="freeText8647704863726004547" style="display:none"><b>Update:</b> The first time I read <i>Ambersons</i>, oh so many years ago, I was entranced. I felt I had stumbled upon a lost treasure and was equally repulsed and bewitched by the character at the center, young Georgie Minafer. After reading it a second time, my admiration for the Georgie character is unchanged, even as I find myself questioning other aspects of the book. In particular, I object to the presentation of the book's few African American characters and think Tarkington ultimately goes too easy on Prince Georgie. Despite these complaints, I still find the book eminently readable and, like its namesake family, rather close to magnificent.<br /><br /><b>Original review (2009):</b><br />1919 Booth Tarkington won the Pulitzer for this book. A couple years later he won a second Pulitzer -- and become the first author to receive a second Pulitzer -- with <i>Alice Adams</i>. He was the nation's eminent writer of fiction. In the ninety years since then, however, Tarkington has become less and less a respected and talked-about writer, more and more a footnote in American literary history (and in Orson Welles biographies). Funny how his own fame so closely resembles that of the family of the <i>Magnificent Ambersons</i>.<br /><br />This is an excellent novel. From start to finish. It is comic, educational and tender. It is a study into the character of a marginally likable fallen-from-riches young man, and, more than that, it is an epic depiction of the American town-turned-metropolis at the start of the Twentieth Century with the emergence of the "horseless carriage". <i>The Magnificent Ambersons</i> is a breezy read at less than 300 pages; it is the sort of book that could go on for three times as many pages without any diminishment in this reader's pleasure. I even put off reading the last couple chapters for a few days, just to prolong the time I could spend with Georgie, Aunt Fannie, and the rest of the family and its acquaintances.<br /><br />Obviously, <i>Ambersons</i> was a topical book at the time of its release. Still in recent memory were the invention of the automobile and the industrialization of the American town. I haven't looked for time-of-release reviews of the book, but I'll jump out on a limb anyway and say that Tarkington's audiences probably found the story nostalgic, reminiscent of a not-so-distant but definitely <i>gone</i> aristocratic past. They probably chuckled at the characters' use of insults that were even then archaic ("riffraff!") as well as at the characters' reluctance to believe the gas-propelled vehicle could ever be more than a novelty. Young Georgie Amberson, who rides his horse ahead of the earlier, weaker models of the automobile and yells "Git a hoss! Git a hoss!", just can't believe that these disgusting, loud, plebeian inventions have any practical value. He would have fallen off his horse if he knew then that the automobile would not only run over his horse's future, but also his own.<br /><br />The book is topical now, too, with the once-almighty American automobile industry in uncertain financial straits, and given what we know now about the lethal consequences of the particulate pollution that emanates from horseless carriages. Sometimes we pretend that concerns over pollution and (to a lesser extent) global warming are new. But here they are, in Booth Tarkington's ninety-year-old book, when Lucy has to replace her white curtains with darker ones that don't show the soot that collects daily on her windowsill. Some of those naysayers, maybe even Georgie Amberson, would revel today to know that the automobile industry that pillaged their towns has now received its own "comeuppance" -- but like so many people who wish for "comeuppances", Georgie and the people who witnessed the birth of the automobile have not lived to see their revenge fantasies become realities.<br /><br />Maybe <i>The Magnificent Ambersons</i> is an even better book now than it was in 1919. It's been a long time since I've read a book so enjoyable yet so harrowing. Whatever it is, it is a must-read. Get to it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8647704863726004547" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


